[1] Note that, in the situation where you have extreme outliers, this can be due to:
[1] 1) data entry errors, measurement errors or unusual values.
[1] You can include the outlier in the analysis anyway if you do not believe the result will be substantially affected.
[1] This can be evaluated by comparing the result of the ANOVA test with and without the outlier.
[1] It’s also possible to keep the outliers in the data and perform robust ANOVA test using the WRS2 package.
[1] 
[1] 
[1] 2) Checking normality assumption
[1] # Building the linear model
[1] # Creating a QQ plot of residuals
[1] ### Compute Shapiro-Wilk test of normality ###
# A tibble: 1 × 3
  variable         statistic p.value
  <chr>                <dbl>   <dbl>
1 residuals(model)     0.995   0.783
[1] In the QQ plot, as all the points fall approximately along the reference line, we can assume normality.
[1] This conclusion is supported by the Shapiro-Wilk test. The p-value is not significant (p = 0.783404961988034),
[1] so we can assume normality.
[1] 
[1] 3) Checking homogeneity of variance assumption
[1] This can be checked using the Levene’s test:
# A tibble: 1 × 4
    df1   df2 statistic      p
  <int> <int>     <dbl>  <dbl>
1     2   189      4.44 0.0131
[1] The Levene’s test is not significant (p > 0.0130631564309247). Therefore, we can assume the homogeneity of variances in the different groups.
[1] ### Computation of the one-way ANOVA test ###
[1] In the R code below, the asterisk represents the interaction effect and the main effect of each variable (and all lower-order interactions).
