[1] ### Check assumptions ###
[1] 1) Checking the presence of outliers
[1] No outliers found: This assumption is verified
[1] 
[1] 2) Checking normality assumption
[1] # Building the linear model
[1] # Creating a QQ plot of residuals
[1] ### Compute Shapiro-Wilk test of normality ###
# A tibble: 1 × 3
  variable         statistic p.value
  <chr>                <dbl>   <dbl>
1 residuals(model)     0.990   0.209
[1] In the QQ plot, as all the points fall approximately along the reference line, we can assume normality.
[1] This conclusion is supported by the Shapiro-Wilk test. The p-value is not significant (p = 0.208526491727801),
[1] so we can assume normality.
[1] 
[1] 3) Checking homogeneity of variance assumption
[1] This can be checked using the Levene’s test:
# A tibble: 1 × 4
    df1   df2 statistic       p
  <int> <int>     <dbl>   <dbl>
1     2   189      5.15 0.00667
[1] The Levene’s test is not significant (p > 0.00667145272938525). Therefore, we can assume the homogeneity of variances in the different groups.
